PXE NETBOOT — HTTP FETCH MACROS
════════════════════════════════════════════════

These reproduce, by hand, the HTTP GETs that iPXE performs after it boots:
it fetches boot.ipxe, then the `kernel` and `initrd` URLs that script names.
Doing them yourself — and watching the status line + headers come back — is
the quickest way to see exactly what your VM's iPXE will (or won't) get.

LAUNCH (raw HTTP over TCP, CRLF line endings, from the HOST):
  socwrap.sh --macros --macro-file macros/pxe-fetch.json --crlf -t localhost 8181

  NOTE on host vs. port:
    From the host the netboot nginx is on  localhost:8181  (TLS: localhost:8443).
    `10.0.2.2:8181` is the QEMU slirp gateway — that address only resolves
    INSIDE a slirp VM, so connect to localhost when probing from the host.

SET TARGETS (defaults match the minimal-netboot lab; override for distro labs):
  //set HOST localhost           Host: header value
  //set KERNEL /kernel           kernel path (Rocky/Alma labs: /vmlinuz)
  //set INITRD /initrd.gz        initrd path (Rocky/Alma labs: /initrd.img)

REQUEST PIECES (type one per line, blank line ends the request):
  //get-kernel    GET {{KERNEL}}      //get-initrd   GET {{INITRD}}
  //get-bootipxe  GET /boot.ipxe      //get  GET {{PATH}} (set PATH first)
  //host          Host: {{HOST}}      //ua    User-Agent: iPXE-like
  //accept-any    Accept: */*         //close Connection: close
  //end           blank line — sends the request, triggers the response

FULL WALKTHROUGHS (auto-stepped, good for --record):
  //demo-bootipxe   Fetch boot.ipxe and read it back (what iPXE chainloads)
  //demo-kernel     Full GET of the kernel — request + response headers
  //demo-chain      The whole iPXE sequence: boot.ipxe → kernel → initrd

NOTES:
  - HTTP/1.1 needs a Host: header; nginx serves the file regardless of its value.
  - HEAD instead of GET (//get → change to HEAD) returns headers with no body —
    handy to confirm Content-Length without pulling a 300 MB initrd.
  - For TFTP (fetching ipxe.efi the way firmware does), use the tftp client +
    macros/tftp.json instead — TFTP is binary UDP, not hand-typable over TCP.
  - Record any session:  socwrap.sh --record run.cast ...   then  --replay run.cast
